<h2 id="implementation-reality">🛠️ Implementation Reality Check</h2>

Marketing materials say "set up in 30 minutes." Here's what actually happens.

For a straightforward Shopify store with standard subscription options, expect 2-3 days to properly configure and test the platform. This includes setting up subscription options, configuring the customer portal, connecting payment processing, and testing the subscriber flow end-to-end.

For multi-location operators or those with complex product catalogs, budget 2-3 weeks for proper implementation. You'll need to map inventory sync logic, configure location-based rules, test edge cases, and train staff on the new system. We've seen operators try to rush this and spend months cleaning up the resulting customer service disasters.

The migration process from another subscription platform is its own project. Recharge provides migration tools, but subscriber history, saved payment methods, and upcoming renewal dates all need careful handling. Our recommendation: run parallel systems for one billing cycle when possible, even though it adds cost. The customer experience protection is worth it.

<h2 id="alternatives-worth-considering">🔄 Alternatives Worth Considering</h2>

While Recharge leads our recommendations for most operators, context matters.

**Bold Subscriptions** offers lower base pricing and works well for operators under $30K monthly subscription revenue. The feature set is more limited, but if you need basic subscribe-and-save functionality without complex logic, it handles that competently.

**Smartrr** has emerged as a strong competitor with particularly good customer portal experiences. Their membership features are more native than Recharge's, making them worth evaluating if community and membership are core to your subscription model.

**Ordergroove** targets enterprise operators with $500K+ monthly subscription revenue. Their relationship-based pricing and white-glove service make sense at that scale, but they're overkill (and overpriced) for most operators.

**Skio** is the new entrant getting attention in 2026. Their password-less login and modern UX are compelling, but we haven't seen enough at-scale implementations to recommend them for operators who can't afford platform risk.

